Atmospheric dispersion modeling was performed using the RMP*Comp program distributed by the Chemical Emergency Preparedness and Prevention Office of the United States Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA).  This model determines the distance traveled by chlorine and sulfur dioxide released until concentrations decrease to the "toxic endpoint" of 0.0087 milligrams per Liter (mg/L) and 0.0078 mg/L, respectively, as selected by USEPA.  The chlorine toxic endpoint of 0.0087 mg/L in air and sulfur dioxide toxic endpoint of 0.0078 mg/L in air both represent the American Industrial Hygiene Association (AIHA) Emergency Response Planning Guideline (ERPG)-2, defined as the "maximum airborne concentration below which it is believed that nearly all individuals could be exposed for up to 1 hour without experiencing or developing irreversible or other serious health effects or symptoms which could impair an individual's ability to take protective action".  This amount corresponds to 3.0 parts per million by volume.   



The Hanover WWTP Accidental Release Prevention Program is based upon the following elements:

1.    Routine training for the operators;

2.    Preventative maintenance program for equipment;

3.    Use of industry-standard process and safety equipment;

4.    Use of effective standard operating procedures, written with the participation of the operators;

5.    Performance of a Hazard Review of the equipment and procedures; and

6.    Implementation of an auditing and inspection program.



